# Spring Boot Anti-Bug Rules (Top 40)

1. No business logic in controllers.
2. No repository access from controllers.
3. No entity exposure in API responses.
4. Keep DTO validation at API boundary.
5. Keep transaction boundary in service layer only.
6. Never catch-and-ignore exceptions.
7. Never leak stacktrace to API clients.
8. Always return standardized `error_code`.
9. Always include `trace_id` in error responses.
10. Never use broad `Exception` for business flow control.
11. Use optimistic locking for mutable aggregates.
12. Avoid EAGER relationships by default.
13. Prevent N+1 in list and detail query flows.
14. Require pagination for all list endpoints.
15. Enforce max page size.
16. Ensure deterministic sorting in pagination.
17. Add indexes for frequent filters and joins.
18. Avoid `SELECT *` in native SQL.
19. Use projections for read-heavy endpoints.
20. Validate data invariants before save/update.
21. Never trust client-supplied IDs without authorization check.
22. Never deserialize untrusted polymorphic payloads blindly.
23. Ensure idempotency for retry-prone write APIs.
24. Apply rate limits to brute-force sensitive endpoints.
25. Enforce JWT issuer/audience/expiry checks.
26. Rotate JWT signing keys with migration strategy.
27. Never log secrets, tokens, passwords, or full PII.
28. Use structured logging with consistent fields.
29. Propagate correlation id across async boundaries.
30. Set explicit DB and Redis timeouts.
31. Set explicit HTTP client timeouts and retries.
32. Use circuit breaker for unstable external dependencies.
33. Define Redis TTL for each cache namespace.
34. Keep cache invalidation aligned with write transactions.
35. Protect against cache stampede on hot keys.
36. Add readiness and liveness checks.
37. Add integration test for every critical repository query.
38. Add contract tests for public APIs.
39. Fail CI when tests or lint checks fail.
40. Never deploy without rollback-ready artifact and script.
